Place Stanislas, Place de la Carrière, and Place d'Alliance in Nancy, France, represent a significant moment in human history, particularly in the context of urban planning and architectural design. Recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983, this ensemble is a masterpiece of 18th-century town planning, embodying the ideals of the Age of Enlightenment and influencing urban development across Europe and beyond [lavoiebleue](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-0), [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-1), [nancy-tourisme](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-2), [assofrance-patrimoinemondial](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-3), [unesco](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-4), [medium](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-0), [worldheritagesites](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-2).

The creation of these squares by Stanisław Leszczyński, the former King of Poland and Duke of Lorraine, between 1752 and 1756, was intended to link the medieval old town of Nancy with its "new" town, creating a unified and modernized urban center [newworldencyclopedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-5), [visitacity](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-6), [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-1), [frenchmoments](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/0-7), [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-1), [mycityhunt](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-3), [nancy-tourisme](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-4). The neoclassical style, adorned with elegant balconies and intricate stonework, along with features like the Arc Héré, inspired public spaces and buildings in other European cities [travelfranceonline](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-8), [francerent](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-5), [wikipedia](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-9), [mycityhunt](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/id/1-3).
